{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/haematospermia/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"33ea3bd8-6b04-5d82-b5df-74af25fafe82","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field ce2c5aa3-03e8-45c6-8a02-932b5b182ab2 --><h1>Haematospermia: Summary</h1><!-- end field ce2c5aa3-03e8-45c6-8a02-932b5b182ab2 -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 65cc6911-fd3d-4403-83b3-4b71400b284f --><!-- begin field 144b5473-b334-482b-ab8b-01cc51f762a7 --><ul><li>Haematospermia is the visible presence of blood in the semen. The blood appears bright red when bleeding has occurred recently and red/brown when it is old.</li><li>In most cases, haematospermia is benign and self-limiting.</li><li>In men younger than 40 years of age, the most common cause of haematospermia is infection.</li><li>In men of 40 years old and older, an underlying malignancy is a more common cause than in men below the age of 40 years.</li><li>Investigations include:<ul><li>Measurement of blood pressure.</li><li>Culture and analysis of a mid-stream urine sample.</li><li>Examination of testes to detect lumps, tenderness, and/or swelling.</li><li>Digital rectal examination to assess the prostate.</li><li>Other investigations guided by clinical findings, for example, tests for sexually transmitted infections, full blood count, coagulation screen, renal and liver function tests, and scrotal ultrasound (if there is a testicular swelling).</li></ul></li><li>Management in men younger than 40 years includes:<ul><li>Treatment of an underlying cause if identified.</li><li>If an underlying cause is not identified, providing reassurance that a serious underlying cause is very unlikely and that the condition will likely be self-limiting.</li><li>Referral to a urologist if there are more than ten episodes of haematospermia.</li></ul></li><li>Management in men 40 years and older includes referral to a urologist for further assessment after even one episode of haematospermia (unless the man has had a recent prostate biopsy).</li></ul><!-- end field 144b5473-b334-482b-ab8b-01cc51f762a7 --><!-- end item 65cc6911-fd3d-4403-83b3-4b71400b284f -->","topic":{"id":"12090f33-1ccd-51f2-a188-a88eda1af886","topicId":"0e921775-3261-4ad5-a148-d994469f6d8a","topicName":"Haematospermia","slug":"haematospermia","aliases":[],"chapters":[{"id":"33ea3bd8-6b04-5d82-b5df-74af25fafe82","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"6fcbdbf0-d1be-5d09-aa34-cb18c960141e","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","subChapters":[]},{"id":"e813a119-1756-5d85-bc2e-26323784c06e","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","subChapters":[{"id":"1fa5d310-8049-5d57-9d34-47566fa109ef","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"d374d4ed-3587-59f9-8e8e-7af2cc46dde8","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"a7232592-5f3f-52c7-aeda-ea292a5c7341","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","subChapters":[{"id":"922acd0f-5925-5af1-bb00-e41668aad6b5","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"537c77ea-3239-584d-bbf2-4d31f7dfab67","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"9d929ecd-fcf3-5668-9269-e20cec2c6064","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"8d843052-b714-50ac-a6a7-b2ebf7217daf","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"bc160ca6-1602-5d69-9a21-2a97954a1542","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - options for local implementation"},{"id":"50893e21-c31f-500e-9150-bcfad7b9c3c8","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"NICE Quality standards"}]},{"id":"90069248-8556-57c1-b357-a921babf059c","slug":"background-information","fullItemName":"Background information","subChapters":[{"id":"e1ea5fc6-699e-5c7c-b379-abcb22135245","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition"},{"id":"a6